# 7. Montana/Wyoming utility rate and backup-power cost impact

## Utility-rate structure

Montana and Wyoming clinic utility costs will vary depending on whether each site is served by:

- Investor-owned utility;
- Rural electric cooperative;
- Municipal utility;
- Small commercial rate class;
- Demand-metered account;
- Facility-charge-heavy cooperative tariff.

Typical relevant structures include:

- Energy charge in $/kWh;
- Monthly facility/customer charge;
- Possible demand charge in $/kW;
- Seasonal variation;
- Cooperative-specific riders or minimum bills.

Example rate context from panel evidence:

- Wyoming commercial rates are often around **$0.09–$0.10/kWh**;
- Montana commercial rates are often around **$0.10–$0.11/kWh**;
- Some rural cooperatives may have lower energy charges, e.g., around **$0.06–$0.08/kWh**, but higher fixed monthly charges.

Final TCO should use each clinic’s actual utility bill and tariff.

## Backup-power energy cost per outage

Using an estimated tariff range of **$0.07–$0.12/kWh**, the direct grid energy cost to recharge/run backup power for a 12-hour event is very small:

| Product | 12-hour kWh per unit | 12-hour cost per unit at $0.07/kWh | 12-hour cost per unit at $0.12/kWh |
|---|---:|---:|---:|
| Helmer iPR125-GX | 1.545 kWh | $0.11 | $0.19 |
